CAMgJ9muI3hV-DAYS_7GgahKhkFA7gT9-mX0cMmTZu0ab72c7bCnPJp9lQq-qShnjuYCO-yQq2Q=
0VEgD8Eb0lPFBNfIG-6JEgqFMkwZYLNhNTUfgPZjXIOzNaR4bWBMBVqM9VzCKJXjPfF2UtISziX=
RDsiIKe1vrj18gOjAwA_kM0VAq1lq3cuDfT3od4vW-4Wcug18OLbOpa0138v59OAg1mzX8HvBn5=
v9nF6eAtgk9SR7pgAFQzElhGBCqCCUdrTjvbYS6Ki4phKU7qYXEULF8OB4m2lXjrFU614fFsomp=
jqmHOLcxq_FbrBeg_b20Op2xFDPAaIdV_C3kXqLvRwNM0TITbgfbG06mZCSYI2ZpreBpowzpnqt=
CGpkn9pW_If-AWnCkC0], Chris Dixon wrote about why centralized platforms alw=
ays do this. In the early days, centralized platforms do anything they can =
to attract users, developers, and businesses in order to build up multi-sid=
ed network effects.=C2=A0
Once they=E2=80=99ve built those network effects, though, and they know tha=
t users, developers, and businesses are locked in, they switch from =E2=80=
=9Cattract=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cextract.=E2=80=9D The easiest way to grow r=
evenue is to start charging businesses and developers to reach customers, a=
nd to serve customers ads or products based on the data they=E2=80=99ve acc=
umulated.=C2=A0
This isn=E2=80=99t evil. It=E2=80=99s just how the incentives work. Users a=
nd creators are free to move, although currently, moving to a new platform =
does mean leaving behind the data, friends, points, followers, likes, asset=
s, and other digital artifacts they=E2=80=99ve created on the platform.=C2=
=A0
It would be easy to look at Connect and say that we=E2=80=99re in the =E2=
=80=9Cattract=E2=80=9D stage of Facebook=E2=80=99s Metaverse development, a=
nd that they=E2=80=99ll once again switch to =E2=80=9Cextract=E2=80=9D as s=
oon as humanly possible. Which is probably true, except that it might not b=
e possible.=C2=A0
Companies and protocols exist inside of a broader ecosystem. Web 2.0 platfo=
rms could extract because all of the other Web 2.0 platforms were extractin=
g, and because users and builders are loath to give up everything they=E2=
=80=99ve built there. There was nowhere else to go, and even the alternativ=
es that looked attractive had no built-in guarantees that they wouldn=E2=80=
=99t make their heel turn one day, too.=C2=A0
Crypto, as they say, fixes this.=C2=A0
In some cases, on a local level, web3 means that strong commitments are wri=
tten into the code itself. The web3 version of Facebook might not be able t=
o arbitrarily change algorithms on which entire businesses and industries h=
ad come to rely. That=E2=80=99s important.=C2=A0
But there=E2=80=99s an equally important force, the one that keeps OpenSea =
in line: competition combined with portability of assets. If OpenSea were t=
o start charging 5% or 10% or certainly 30% to sit in between sellers and b=
uyers, people would move their business to another platform immediately. Fo=
r decentralized protocols, which are open source by default, the threat of =
being forked serves as an incentive to treat both the supply and demand sid=
e well, and to keep fees as low as possible.=C2=A0
Protocols aren=E2=80=99t businesses themselves. Protocols are minimally ext=
ractive coordinators.=C2=A0
Protocols as Minimally Extractive Coordinators
In 2019, Chris Burniske [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMGuhCAM_Jrla=
KCIwoHDu-xvGNDqEhUM1Lfx7x-7Hl7StGkm0-nM6AiXlC97pELs0wa6DrQR32VDIszsLJiHMFnR=
gZaqNWyy7SS00iyUYc6IuwubpXwiO06_hdFRSPHL4BwUe1mvhePaqF4qlDB7Yfzcd9ogVw74aG5=
dd04B44gWfzFfKSLb7IvoKA_584BnLXqHz0fNmPa6jf7MMZQVWbDAQQjBhQAlABpo2s64HsHr1k=
CP2jTzKpTSMTxavi_QlNMXcuP6ucWyjYl8yiEuFV5fbsftC1Q_Q537GQNdA0bnN5xuq3Qn9jU_L=
Bgx1ySnwVHNSaq-F9xwaeC2VrNopdSd0YJV5SlVVvwX_QNVA4Iu] wrote one of the most =
useful essays out there for understanding web3: Protocols as Minimally Extr=
active Coordinators [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkUGOwyAMRU9Tdo2AQ=
AILFrOZa0QEnASVQAROO7n9MO1iJNtf8pf1pWdnEdZcLnPkiuRvTHgdYBK8agREKOSsUKbgDRu4=
6qXQxBvhmZKKhDotBWC3IRosJ5DjnGNwFkNO7wtKuSSbUVZ6Kq2mi_JKLAsD0WsmFklBKLaMn1x=
7-gDJgYEnlCsnINFsiEe99V83_t3q9Xp1R7QOthw9lO7p2nKOeW3CKdNNGG1jaH2UjNnlWO-23v=
eQwm5jvO7wg8U6DE-4u5yLD8liLpUEwylnjFHGuGScd7wTg7Yj8FkJzUdQulseTEqVwk3QfeVdP=
eeK1j06l3dSTMo45xLS2uzHZneIb6MhmZruZwp4TZDsHMF_aOEH-pvftEKC0p7hJ4sNdS_HkVFN=
e80_dBpO0fdq0IqRluxzu0r_ob8S0plD].=C2=A0
In it, he laid out a short but compelling argument that protocols will need=
 to extract as little value as possible or risk being abandoned or forked (=
essentially copied). You should take a couple of minutes and read it, but t=
his summarizes it well:=C2=A0
Protocols provide structure for businesses, but are not businesses themselv=
es; they are systems of logic that coordinate exchange between suppliers (b=
usinesses) and consumers of a service.=C2=A0 As coordinators of exchange, p=
rotocols should be minimally extractive, whereas businesses are incentivize=
d to be maximally extractive (that=E2=80=99s profit, and a business is valu=
ed as a multiple of its profit).=C2=A0
From this angle, protocols can be seen as routers of economic activity. Jus=
t as the routers of the internet are as lean and efficient as possible, so =
too should crypto=E2=80=99s protocols trend. The less extractive a protocol=
 is in coordinating exchange, the more that form of exchange will happen.
Protocols can still charge fees. They shouldn=E2=80=99t lose money. They ca=
n become incredibly, incredibly valuable (see: Bitcoin, Ethereum, Uniswap, =
and on and on). But if they charge fees that are too high, they=E2=80=99ll =
lose. As Burniske put it, =E2=80=9CAny unnecessary extraction from the proc=
ess of exchange is a tax that will ultimately be weeded out by copy-paste c=
ompetition in the world of open-source protocols.=E2=80=9D This applies to =
fees directly, and also to the protocol=E2=80=99s decision and actions.=C2=
=A0
When Tron=E2=80=99s Justin Sun bought Steemit, the people who ran the Steem=
 blockchain executed a soft fork [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUcGu=
4yAM_JpySwQEUnLg8C7vNyISnIRtAhGYRv37dduVVkIey9Ywo_HsENaUX_ZMBdm7jPg6wUa4yg6=
IkFktkMfgreil6bQamLfKC6MNC2VcMsDhwm4xV2BnnfYwOwwpfhicS802K4TXyoD3Ano1GdUvcp=
nkssx-WbTs4avrqg8QZ7DwhPxKEdhuN8Sz3Lqfm_yld11XO6cQPZQHNQeNEOaNQHLJCbh894rKn=
1owxKbU2Eyprhs2Bclp-IfNkZ7gG0zNHt7DLZTmTBdkorJg6TshBBdCaiFlK1vVD-4OkrwP8g5m=
aJeH0NrEcFP8WGVb6lTQzR9XLNuYcEo5xJXWj80dsH8WFM9IeNQY8DVCdNMO_pscfg_wyXJcIUK=
mw_jRIcXe6ftd8IF3g_wmRdGqrjP9YAQjZZ-IFf-L_gXVip1Q] of the blockchain to kee=
p him from being able to control it. When some Uniswap users were unhappy t=
hat Uniswap hadn=E2=80=99t issued a token, they forked it and created Sushi=
Swap. After both forks, users were free to vote with their feet and dollars=
 between alternatives.=C2=A0
This is the same way that Epic CEO Tim Sweeney, the closest thing we have t=
o a Godfather of the Metaverse, believes that the platforms underpinning th=
e Metaverse should operate. In a July 2020 interview with Deconstructor of =
Fun [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkDtuxDAMRE-zKg19vVKhIk2uYehDe4W1J=
UOiY_j2UdZFAIIsBuQMX3AIS6mX3UtD8tcmvHawGc62AiJUcjSoU4qWjVwLJQ2JVkamlSapTXMF=
2FxaLdYDyH74NQWHqeTPBqVckZcdqRyFClEJLc3Mg3CMzrM0wlPPpYfb1x0xQQ5g4QfqVTKQ1b4=
Q9_YQXw_-3es8zyFCKLl1t4Cllnk-8hDK1kW_lqUPTFs7ATJcJFlOOWOMMsYV43zggxyNewL3PQ=
d_gjbD_GZK6Zwekm4LH9rhG7rw_rtJqs0FfakpL11-v9wG60fob059bkdOeE2QnV8h3gTwBvlhM=
i09Ru2A4-Sw4xPq-WTUUGH4_XFHJIXQo9GMdOdY-lb-N_0FqByLPQ], he made the case fo=
r open app stores that are subject to the forces of competition instead of =
the closed and =E2=80=9Cfake open=E2=80=9D app stores that Apple and Google=
, respectively, run today. Sweeney thinks that platforms in the Metaverse s=
hould essentially charge enough to cover their costs plus a reasonable marg=
in, but that they should be subject to market forces:=C2=A0
I think the key is that the economics be completely transparent... I think =
transparency and open competition there are the critical elements of it.
Sweeney is a missionary for the Metaverse, but he=E2=80=99s also a capitali=
st, and one fiduciarily obligated to increase Epic=E2=80=99s long-term shar=
eholder value. He wants Epic to make a lot of money, he just understands th=
at in a transparent and open system, the platforms and protocols on top of =
which the most activity occurs will be the ones that are minimally extracti=
ve.=C2=A0
Interestingly, that=E2=80=99s the language that Facebook is using to descri=
be its own plans. Zuck laid out his philosophy for the business model in th=
e Connect video [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkc2KhTAMhZ_GLqXpn3XRx=
cBwX0OqjVqutlLrFd9-enUxEBI4STjhy2AzTjFdZot7Jt_U5WtDE_DcF8wZEzl2TJ13BhTTXIqW=
OCMcaKmJ37sxIa7WLyanA8l29IsfbPYx3BuUMklmM9BRA7QM1ah1LxoqhBMURo4ISgr5-NrDeQw=
DGvxgumJAspg5522v-E_FXiXO86xHO2Af47se4vqVbB7mUhf_we8QfyUcK_57692GabWLD--KqU=
9RpQLJpWq1EFRpTrxhlAEABWASGKtZLVRrG2S9Fi1rULf1-AYpdfCVoOvE6v3o92yH258kE2LuY=
_JhKu33bFdc7kYB0ZW6HsHnq8Ng-wXdwyg_qG9q3YQBU3mB62wugLlsGqAt5S17mBSIgnNdLgZS=
nF0sW-Hf9A9F8JJU] (right around minute 35):
We plan to either subsidize our devices or sell them at cost to make them a=
vailable to more people. We=E2=80=99ll continue supporting side-loading and=
 linking to PCs so consumers and developers have choice, rather than forcin=
g them to use the Quest Store to find apps or reach customers. And we=E2=80=
=99ll aim to offer developer and creator services with low fees in as many =
cases as possible so we can maximize the overall creator economy, while rec=
ognizing that to keep investing in this future, we=E2=80=99ll need to keep =
some fees higher for some period to make sure that we don=E2=80=99t lose to=
o much money on this project.=C2=A0
To understand how Meta=E2=80=99s VR / Strategy has evolved, why the AppleVe=
rse would be a dark place, and why I think Facebook will have no choice but=
 to follow through on the open vision it painted at Connect=E2=80=A6=20
