and developers to reach customers, and to serve customers ads or products b=
ased on the data they&#8217;ve accumulated.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a=
1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">This isn&#821=
7;t evil. It&#8217;s just how the incentives work. Users and creators are f=
ree to move, although currently, moving to a new platform does mean leaving=
 behind the data, friends, points, followers, likes, assets, and other digi=
tal artifacts they&#8217;ve created on the platform.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">It w=
ould be easy to look at Connect and say that we&#8217;re in the &#8220;attr=
act&#8221; stage of Facebook&#8217;s Metaverse development, and that they&#=
8217;ll once again switch to &#8220;extract&#8221; as soon as humanly possi=
ble. Which is probably true, except that it might not be possible.&nbsp;</p=
><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 1em 0;">Companies and protocols exist inside of a broader ecosystem. Web =
2.0 platforms could extract because all of the other Web 2.0 platforms were=
 extracting, and because users and builders are loath to give up everything=
 they&#8217;ve built there. There was nowhere else to go, and even the alte=
rnatives that looked attractive had no built-in guarantees that they wouldn=
&#8217;t make their heel turn one day, too.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a=
1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Crypto, as th=
ey say, fixes this.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">In some cases, on a local level, web3=
 means that strong commitments are written into the code itself. The web3 v=
ersion of Facebook might not be able to arbitrarily change algorithms on wh=
ich entire businesses and industries had come to rely. That&#8217;s importa=
nt.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">But there&#8217;s an equally important force, the one=
 that keeps OpenSea in line: <strong>competition combined with portability =
of assets</strong>. If OpenSea were to start charging 5% or 10% or certainl=
y 30% to sit in between sellers and buyers, people would move their busines=
s to another platform immediately. For decentralized protocols, which are o=
pen source by default, the threat of being forked serves as an incentive to=
 treat both the supply and demand side well, and to keep fees as low as pos=
sible.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 2=
6px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Protocols aren&#8217;t businesses themselves. Prot=
ocols are minimally extractive coordinators.&nbsp;</p><h3 style=3D"-moz-osx=
-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; color: #=
1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFon=
t, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', '=
Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; =
line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;"><strong>Protocols as Minimal=
ly Extractive Coordinators</strong></h3><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">In 2019, <a href=3D"https:=
//email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMGuhCAM_JrlaKCIwoHDu-xvGNDqEhUM1Lfx7x-7Hl7S=
tGkm0-nM6AiXlC97pELs0wa6DrQR32VDIszsLJiHMFnRgZaqNWyy7SS00iyUYc6IuwubpXwiO06=
_hdFRSPHL4BwUe1mvhePaqF4qlDB7Yfzcd9ogVw74aG5dd04B44gWfzFfKSLb7IvoKA_584BnLX=
qHz0fNmPa6jf7MMZQVWbDAQQjBhQAlABpo2s64HsHr1kCP2jTzKpTSMTxavi_QlNMXcuP6ucWyj=
Yl8yiEuFV5fbsftC1Q_Q537GQNdA0bnN5xuq3Qn9jU_LBgx1ySnwVHNSaq-F9xwaeC2VrNopdSd=
0YJV5SlVVvwX_QNVA4Iu" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: un=
derline;">Chris Burniske</a> wrote one of the most useful essays out there =
for understanding web3: <em><a href=3D"https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJx=
FkUGOwyAMRU9Tdo2AQAILFrOZa0QEnASVQAROO7n9MO1iJNtf8pf1pWdnEdZcLnPkiuRvTHgdYB=
K8agREKOSsUKbgDRu46qXQxBvhmZKKhDotBWC3IRosJ5DjnGNwFkNO7wtKuSSbUVZ6Kq2mi_JKL=
AsD0WsmFklBKLaMn1x7-gDJgYEnlCsnINFsiEe99V83_t3q9Xp1R7QOthw9lO7p2nKOeW3CKdNN=
GG1jaH2UjNnlWO-23veQwm5jvO7wg8U6DE-4u5yLD8liLpUEwylnjFHGuGScd7wTg7Yj8FkJzUd=
QulseTEqVwk3QfeVdPeeK1j06l3dSTMo45xLS2uzHZneIb6MhmZruZwp4TZDsHMF_aOEH-pvftE=
KC0p7hJ4sNdS_HkVFNe80_dBpO0fdq0IqRluxzu0r_ob8S0plD" rel=3D"" style=3D"color=
: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Protocols as Minimally Extractive C=
oordinators</a>.</em>&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">In it, he laid out a short but comp=
elling argument that protocols will need to extract as little value as poss=
ible or risk being abandoned or forked (essentially copied). You should tak=
e a couple of minutes and read it, but this summarizes it well:&nbsp;</p><b=
lockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;"><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; =
margin-left: 1em;"><em><strong>Protocols provide structure for businesses</=
strong>, but are not businesses themselves; <strong>they are systems of log=
ic that coordinate exchange between suppliers (businesses) and consumers of=
 a service</strong>.&nbsp; As coordinators of exchange, <strong>protocols s=
hould be minimally extractive</strong>, whereas businesses are incentivized=
 to be maximally extractive (that&#8217;s profit, and a business is valued =
as a multiple of its profit).&nbsp;</em></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em>=
From this angle, <strong>protocols can be seen as routers of economic activ=
ity</strong>. Just as the routers of the internet are as lean and efficient=
 as possible, so too should crypto&#8217;s protocols trend. <strong>The les=
s extractive a protocol is in coordinating exchange, the more that form of =
exchange will happen.</strong></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1a1=
a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Protocols can =
still charge fees. They shouldn&#8217;t lose money. They can become incredi=
bly, incredibly valuable (see: Bitcoin, Ethereum, Uniswap, and on and on). =
But if they charge fees that are <em>too</em> high, they&#8217;ll lose. As =
Burniske put it, &#8220;Any unnecessary extraction from the process of exch=
ange is a <strong>tax that will ultimately be weeded out by copy-paste comp=
etition in the world of open-source protocols</strong>.&#8221; This applies=
 to fees directly, and also to the protocol&#8217;s decision and actions.&n=
bsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 1em 0;">When Tron&#8217;s Justin Sun bought Steemit, the people wh=
o ran the Steem blockchain <a href=3D"https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxF=
UcGu4yAM_JpySwQEUnLg8C7vNyISnIRtAhGYRv37dduVVkIey9Ywo_HsENaUX_ZMBdm7jPg6wUa=
4yg6IkFktkMfgreil6bQamLfKC6MNC2VcMsDhwm4xV2BnnfYwOwwpfhicS802K4TXyoD3Ano1Gd=
Uvcpnkssx-WbTs4avrqg8QZ7DwhPxKEdhuN8Sz3Lqfm_yld11XO6cQPZQHNQeNEOaNQHLJCbh89=
4rKn1owxKbU2Eyprhs2Bclp-IfNkZ7gG0zNHt7DLZTmTBdkorJg6TshBBdCaiFlK1vVD-4OkrwP=
8g5maJeH0NrEcFP8WGVb6lTQzR9XLNuYcEo5xJXWj80dsH8WFM9IeNQY8DVCdNMO_pscfg_wyXJ=
cIUKmw_jRIcXe6ftd8IF3g_wmRdGqrjP9YAQjZZ-IFf-L_gXVip1Q" rel=3D"" style=3D"co=
lor: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">executed a soft fork</a> of the =
blockchain to keep him from being able to control it. When some Uniswap use=
rs were unhappy that Uniswap hadn&#8217;t issued a token, they forked it an=
d created SushiSwap. After both forks, users were free to vote with their f=
eet and dollars between alternatives.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">This is the same wa=
y that Epic CEO Tim Sweeney, the closest thing we have to a Godfather of th=
e Metaverse, believes that the platforms underpinning the Metaverse should =
operate. In a July 2020 <a href=3D"https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkDt=
uxDAMRE-zKg19vVKhIk2uYehDe4W1JUOiY_j2UdZFAIIsBuQMX3AIS6mX3UtD8tcmvHawGc62Ai=
JUcjSoU4qWjVwLJQ2JVkamlSapTXMF2FxaLdYDyH74NQWHqeTPBqVckZcdqRyFClEJLc3Mg3CMz=
rM0wlPPpYfb1x0xQQ5g4QfqVTKQ1b4Q9_YQXw_-3es8zyFCKLl1t4Cllnk-8hDK1kW_lqUPTFs7=
ATJcJFlOOWOMMsYV43zggxyNewL3PQd_gjbD_GZK6Zwekm4LH9rhG7rw_rtJqs0FfakpL11-v9w=
G60fob059bkdOeE2QnV8h3gTwBvlhMi09Ru2A4-Sw4xPq-WTUUGH4_XFHJIXQo9GMdOdY-lb-N_=
0FqByLPQ" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">in=
terview with Deconstructor of Fun</a>, he made the case for open app stores=
 that are subject to the forces of competition instead of the closed and &#=
8220;fake open&#8221; app stores that Apple and Google, respectively, run t=
oday. Sweeney thinks that platforms in the Metaverse should essentially cha=
rge enough to cover their costs plus a reasonable margin, but that they sho=
uld be subject to market forces:&nbsp;</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left:=
 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em>I think =
the key is that the economics be completely transparent... I think transpar=
ency and open competition there are the critical elements of it.</em></p></=
blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Sweeney is a missionary for the Metaverse, but he&#8217=
;s also a capitalist, and one fiduciarily obligated to increase Epic&#8217;=
s long-term shareholder value. He wants Epic to make a lot of money, he jus=
t understands that in a transparent and open system, the platforms and prot=
ocols on top of which the most activity occurs will be the ones that are mi=
nimally extractive.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Interestingly, that&#8217;s the langu=
age that Facebook is using to describe its own plans. Zuck laid out his phi=
losophy for the business model in the <a href=3D"https://email.mg2.substack=
